english:
  title: Epitaph for Minister Heo Chung, Posthumously Titled Mungyeong, Prime Minister of the Left in the Chosŏn Dynasty
  author: Nam Su-mun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the fourth year of Zhengton, in the twelfth lunar month on the day Renyin, Minister of the Left Heo passed from life due to illness at his private residence, having reached the age of seventy-one. The court bestowed upon him the posthumous name Mungyeong. The following spring in the third month on the day Gengshen, the proper authorities conducted his funeral rites and interred him at the sacred ground of Hyangyangni near Wonpyeongbu.

    His son, Vice-Chief of Staff Hu, requested an epitaph for his tomb. As I had shared the examination success with him on two occasions, I could not refuse this duty.

    According to inquiry, the Minister bore the surname Heo, his given name was Chung, and his courtesy name was Jungtong. He was from Hayang County in Gyeongsang Province. His remote ancestor Kangon fathered Sŏchung; Sŏchung fathered Chŏkrin; Chŏkrin fathered Shin; Shin fathered Setong; Setong fathered Hyŏkbu; Hyŏkbu fathered Tŭksŏ; and Tŭksŏ fathered one named Yu, who rose to the rank of General. Yu was stern and disciplined, carefully preserving the family legacy. He married the daughter of Han Gyun, a man of prominence from Hanyang and Official of the Bureau of Imperial Horses. This union produced Sui, who served as Administrator of the Bureau of Tributary States. Sui possessed a tranquil nature and few desires, always maintaining proper dress and dwelling alone in his chambers. He married the daughter of Secure Official An Munsung, an Attendant-in-Waiting, producing Yunchangwho was rigorous and upright. Yunchangg served as Censor, Official of Regulations, and Junior Assistant, eventually attaining the rank of Keeper of the Right Department. He married the daughter of the Grand Academician Li Chi, producing Kuiyong, who was respectful, capable, and magnanimous with great wisdom. Kuiyong served as Regular Attendant and Director of Maps and Assessments, dying in office as Assistant Commissioner and Military Commandant of Kaesong.

    Kuiyong married the daughter of Yi Gil, Vice Director of Court Ceremonies, and fathered three sons. The eldest, Chu, became Commissioner of the Bureau of Seoul and received the posthumous name Kangsuk. The second was our Minister. The third, Chŏk, served as Vice Director of the Central Council.

    The Minister was born on the eleventh day of the fourth month in the second year of Hongwu, in the year of Kiyou. From childhood he appeared grave and mature. After pursuing learning under Yangchon, the Marquis of Culture and Loyalty Kwon, he devoted himself to study with determination. In the year Kyehai he passed the civil examination; in the year Ülchuk he succeeded in the major examination. In the year Muchen, through hereditary privilege he received appointment as Major. In the year Kyongoh, when Dokkok Sŏng Sekyrin and Songtang Cho Jun conducted examinations at the Ministry of Rites, the Minister was selected in the third rank. Both examiners held him in high regard. He became Administrator of Court Ceremonial.

    In the year Imsin, when our dynasty received the mandate of heaven, he was specially appointed as Left Censor and Drafter of Edicts, soon rising to Administrator of the Bureau of Sacrificial Worship and Drafter of Edicts. At this time, rites and music had fallen into disorder and the functions of the Grand Sacrifice had ceased. The Minister earnestly worked to eliminate habits of neglect, following entirely the ancient precedents. Yangchon frequently praised him, saying, "Surely he will be the one to order our nation's rituals in times to come."

    In the year Kyeyu in the fifth month, he suffered the loss of his father; the following tenth month, the loss of his mother. The people of that time favored Buddhist practices for funeral rites, but the Minister followed entirely the family rites of Master Zhu, performing both grief and ceremony completely. Our nation's scholars and common folk came to practice family rites through his example.

    In the year Jungchuk he became Administrator of the National Academy and revised the ceremonies of the Ritual Sacrifice, which were then promulgated throughout the realm. In the year Kihyo of the era Jianwen, he again served as Left Censor and Drafter of Edicts, earning renown for his forthright integrity. When the Taijong received the succession in the year Kyongchin, he was appointed to the Censorate. When he spoke on matters of state contrary to the throne's wishes, the King grew wrathful and sought to impose severe punishment, questioning him with great harshness. The Minister stood firm in his words, unbending. The King, admiring his unyielding rectitude, demoted him to Magistrate of Wansan. Within months of assuming office, his administration was praised for its excellence. However, he resigned due to illness.

    In autumn of the year Imoh, when a vacancy appeared in the post of Administrator in the Ministry of Personnel, the King, finding the responsibility of selection difficult and lacking a suitable candidate, personally reviewed the official registers. Upon discovering the Minister's name, he declared, "I have found the right man," and appointed him forthwith. That winter he received the rank of Attendant Scholar and became Drafter of Edicts, this too being a special appointment.

    In autumn of Yongnok in the year Kyemi, he was demoted to Magistrate of Ningwol for certain transgressions. That winter he requested retirement due to illness. In the year Kapsin he was recalled as Commander and placed in the Hall of Assembled Worthies. In the year Ülyu he retained these duties while additionally serving as Left Litterateur to the Crown Prince.

    When the King once inquired of the Crown Prince concerning which officials were most capable, the Crown Prince named the Minister. In the year Byŏngsu he became Vice Director of the Bureau for the Heir Apparent. In the year Jŏnghae he served as Director of the Hall of Literary Treasures while maintaining his post as Litterateur. When the Crown Prince journeyed to the Ming capital, the Minister, appointed as Investigator and serving officially in the ceremony, assumed responsibility for all matters concerning the journey. Through his clear contracts and strict command, all people were constrained by fear and dared not violate the prohibitions.

    When the Minister entered the Ming court, he carefully inquired into all matters concerning statecraft and recorded them in detail. Upon his eastern return, he visited the Temple of Confucius at Queli. Discovering that Dong, the Inspector of Gangdo, and Master Rojae of the Heo clan were included among the worthies commemorated there, while Yangxiong was excluded, he submitted memorials to the court advocating these corrections, all of which were implemented.

    In the year Mucha he became Administrator of the Bureau of Provisions and Right Virtue Official to the Crown Prince. The Crown Prince, hearing of his return, remarked to his attendants, "Has Heo the Litterateur returned?" For he had always been somewhat awed by the Minister's severity.

    That year the Pyongyang incident occurred, resulting in numerous arrests. The censorate, overwhelmed by interrogations, falsely implicated the Minister as a witness, resulting in his exile to Chunju. Soon thereafter he was pardoned and appointed Administrator of the Bureau for the Heir Apparent. In the year Sinmyo he was promoted to Counselor in the Ministry of Rites.

    The Minister lamented that the five ritual texts of the Koryŏ period had been lost to time. He therefore drew upon the precedents of the Tang and Song dynasties, compiling comprehensive orderings for the court ceremonies, the cultivation of ritual, and the mourning practices of scholar-officials. Thereafter he became Chief Coordinator of the Bureau for Ritual Orderings. He submitted memorials requesting the establishment of academies and the founding of schools in four directions, both of which were approved. He served as Counselor in both the Ministry of War and Ministry of Personnel.

    In the year Kapoh he was dispatched to inspect the fortified cities of Pyŏngan Province. Most of the measures implemented followed his counsel. When he presented directly to the King the hardships of the Pyŏngan people, the King specially remitted portions of their taxes.

    On another occasion, requesting an audience, he respectfully submitted: "Though martial arts must not be abandoned, riding through treacherous terrain brings dangers beyond measure. I beseech Your Majesty to refrain from personal hunting." His words moved him to tears. He then spoke extensively on the manifold abuses of the many martial fields, which the King greatly appreciated and adopted.

    In spring of the year Ülmi he became Magistrate of Seoul with the rank of Counselor, and that winter Chief Director of the Hall of Literary Treasures. In the year Byŏngsin he was promoted to Vice-Minister of Rites and Chief Coordinator of the Bureau of Sacrificial Worship. He devoted himself carefully to directing and planning the affairs of the latter bureau, correcting what was flawed and restoring what had fallen into disuse, so that all matters, great and small, accorded with proper ritual forms.

    The Minister noted that the levies and taxes upon Kyonggi Province were excessive and the people suffered greatly. He repeatedly requested their reduction. He also noted that the naval forces formed the realm's bulwark, yet were continually depleted by constant campaigns. He begged that they be shown greater consideration. When he later became Prime Minister, his repeated petitions on both these matters were granted.

    In spring of the year Musu he became Deputy Commandant of Kaesong and Concurrent Inspector of Kyonggi Province. That summer he requested retirement due to illness. In autumn when the new King received the succession, he became Magistrate of Kongwon with the rank of Eminent Counselor, and soon thereafter Minister of Rites with the rank of Exemplary Counselor.

    The Minister then offered counsel, saying: "In matters of household and state and all-under-heaven, where the proper relations exist, there must be distinctions between ruler and subject, superior and inferior. In recent times the lower have watched the upper for small openings through which to bring accusations. This tendency cannot be allowed to continue. In the era of Tang Taizong, when a slave accused his master of rebellion, it was not received; indeed, the slave was executed. From now forward, should a slave accuse his master, let him meet this fate. Furthermore, the sage Zhu Xi said to the Song Xiaozong: 'In all litigation, when the lower transgress against the upper or the base show disrespect to the noble, even if their words are true, they should not be upheld; if false, their punishment should exceed that of ordinary offenders.' I beseech that henceforth, when clerks accuse officials, people accuse magistrates or provincial inspectors, unless the accusation concerns the security of the realm or grave crimes of lawless murder, it shall not be prosecuted. False accusations shall be dealt severe punishment, thereby ending the practice of disrespect toward superiors." The King approved these measures.

    In the year Kihae he selected one hundred successful scholars including Sŏng Yigŏm and thirty-three examination graduates including Cho Sangchi. In the year Kyŏngja he selected one hundred successful scholars including Min Wŏn and thirty-three graduates including Ahn Sungson.

    In the year Sinjuk he was appointed Counselor to the State Council. Taijong remarked to the King, "This man is truly a great minister." At a banquet held at the palace at Pungyang, Taijong placed his hand upon the Minister's shoulder and, turning to the King, said, "This is the pillar that supports me." The Minister, startled and moved, wept tears.

    In the fifth month of the year Imim, Taijong passed away. When the great ministers debated the mourning practices for officials, all said, "Since the interment has been completed, it would be appropriate to remove mourning clothes and wear lighter garments while participating in the ancestral rites." But the Minister objected, saying, "Ruler and subject are one body. Now the King's filial piety is sincere and deep, with three years of full mourning. Can it be proper for officials alone to put on their regular clothes immediately after the funeral? Let them wear lighter garments during working hours but full mourning dress during ancestral rites until the mourning period ends." The King ultimately adopted the Minister's counsel. When emissaries from the Ming court came bearing sacrificial gifts and observed the officials in mourning dress participating in the rites, they marveled at the propriety of it.

    When the anniversary of Taijong's death arrived, the Minister observed vegetarian discipline and wept bitterly.

    In autumn he became Minister of Personnel and requested the establishment of a system of long tenure in office—three years for metropolitan officials handling finances and grain, six years for magistrates. He also requested that the ancient law be restored whereby the relatives of criminals would not be permanently barred from office. Both requests were granted.

    In the year Kyemyo he was promoted to the rank of Upholder of Rectitude and given the task of revising the Continued Six Codes. The Minister noted that this work concerned the cultivation of the realm's vital principles and could not be approached hastily. All the severe laws of the time were accordingly modified and crimes were judged according to the existing statutes.

    In the year Byŏngo of the Xuande era, he requested retirement, but instead was appointed Counselor to the Crown Prince's Household. That winter he again became Minister of Personnel. When a remonstrating official faced punishment by flogging, the Minister memorialized, "The remonstrators are the eyes and ears of the sovereign; I beseech that he be shown leniency." The King ordered that the sentence be commuted through payment. Whenever the censorate faced reprimand, the Minister exerted himself to secure relief.

    In the year Jŏngmi he was elevated to the rank of Eminent Uprightness. In the year Musin he requested retirement but instead was appointed Commander of the Central Military Administration. He submitted that since enemies threatened the northeast, the realm should strengthen its preparations. He requested that walls be built from the border regions to the interior, and later asked that offices be established to supervise fortification and shipbuilding, all of which were approved.

    In the year Kiyou, when the King visited the National Academy to pay respects to Confucius and personally examined the students, he commanded the Minister to grade the examinations. The Minister selected three successful candidates including Cho Chu.

    In the year Kyŏngsu he became Counselor to the State Council. In the year Imja he again became Minister of Personnel with the rank of Exemplary Counselor. Over many years of handling appointments, his assessments were fair and discerning. For every position filled, he consulted carefully with colleagues before making recommendations. Bribes and favoritism vanished; filial sons, dutiful grandsons, loyal worthies and capable men were advanced first. Some remarked, "How can there be so many truly filial and dutiful sons?" The Minister replied, "Though some may be false, does not their advancement encourage virtue in the people?"

    Once the King inquired of the Minister concerning the merits and faults of various officials. Many of the notable figures of the time were advanced through his recommendations. Yet the Minister kept secret whom he had suggested, and none knew.

    In spring of the year Kyechuk, when the King intended to campaign against the Jurchen chief Yi Manjuk and the wild peoples of Pachegang, he summoned his great ministers for consultation. All advised that the campaign should proceed. But the Minister objected, saying, "These obstinate peoples, once made enemies, will seek revenge for generations. It is unwise to act hastily." Later, when border commanders urged the King to submit and pacify the Jurchen of Hulladong, the Minister again objected: "These fierce peoples act like men when pleased and like beasts when angered, with appetites as bottomless as gorges. They cannot be pacified." Both objections went unheeded.

    Once when discussing matters in council, when a courtier conveyed the King's order, the Minister submitted a memorial: "In former times, our Taijong kept a sea-hawk but, saying it could not serve as an example to the people, ordered it released. Since it is not to be presented to the central court, let it not be captured and kept." That winter he became Chief Commander.

    In the year Ülmyo he served as Concurrent Director of the National Academy. In the year Jŏngchin of the Zhengton era, he concurrently became Minister of Rites. At this time the examinations stressed literary composition alone. The Minister, desiring to restore the study of the classics, repeatedly requested that the first examination session include classical exposition, but his requests were not granted.

    In spring of the year Jŏngsa, pleading chronic illness, he requested retirement, but permission was not granted. Though he submitted many requests for retirement, each time he was granted exemption from court attendance. That winter his condition worsened. The King sent two imperial physicians to attend him, and visitors came in streams. The Minister, though gravely ill, forced himself to rise, dismissed his attendants, and personally drafted a memorial urging the King to guard against foreign threats, cultivate humility, value good counsel, and respect his ministers. His words were earnest and direct, but his illness prevented him from submitting it.

    In the year Muoh he selected one hundred examination candidates including Shin Sukjou and thirty-three graduates including Ha Wiji. That summer he was elevated to Right Prime Minister and Chief Director of the Hall of Literary Treasures and Hall of Historical Records, and Tutor to the Heir Apparent, with the rank of Great Protector and Exemplary Counselor.

    The Minister had long sought, based on the family rites, to permit scholar-officials to make sacrifices to their great-grandfathers, but his request was not approved. Some years earlier, Japanese merchants had taken up residence in coastal regions, numbering in the thousands and engaging in the salt and fish trade. The Minister repeatedly memorialized, "These people harbor the wolf's ambition; they should all be sent back," and this advice was followed.

    In the eleventh month of winter, great thunder and lightning appeared. The Minister submitted a memorial taking blame and requesting dismissal, but permission was not granted. In the year Kimi, the King bestowed upon him a staff and seat of honor. Shortly thereafter he was elevated to Left Prime Minister and Chief Director of the Hall of Historical Records, his other duties remaining unchanged.

    In the tenth month of winter he fell ill. The King sent physicians with increased frequency, but his condition only worsened. Though he submitted his resignation, it was not accepted. As a mark of comfort and honor, the King specially appointed his son Nul to the post of Director of the Wine Bureau, advancing his rank three steps.

    As his illness grew critical, physicians requested to examine him, but he declined, saying: "I was born in an age of peace, grew to manhood in an age of peace, and now depart in an age of peace. Gazing upward at heaven and downward at earth, I harbor no shame. This is beyond my desert. I reached the age of seventy and rose to Prime Minister, lived in fortunate times, and spoke all that I wished to speak and fulfilled my desires. Thus I die without regret. Yet I wish to see the Chief of Staff." When this was reported to the King, he sent the Chief of Staff Kim Ton to visit. The Minister dismissed his attendants and spoke with him privately on great matters of state.

    From the beginning of his illness until his death, words of concern for the nation never ceased from his lips, and he never once spoke of private affairs. He passed away in tranquility. He had constantly instructed his descendants that all funeral rites should follow the family ritual prescriptions.

    When news of his death was received, the King was greatly grieved. He led the officials in mourning and suspended court proceedings for three days. He sent emissaries to convey condolences and bestowed generous gifts of silk and treasure. The Heir Apparent did likewise. All who heard of his passing, far and near, grieved deeply.

    At the funeral procession, many high officials came to the suburbs to escort the coffin. The Minister's honor in death was thus without regret.

    The Minister possessed a nature both upright and steadfast, pure and cautious, benevolent and forgiving. In his learning he traced back through the philosophical schools of Zhu Xi and the brother Cheng, following the Way of Confucius and Mencius, not seeking mere comprehensiveness. When the rooster crowed he would rise and sit upright. Each day he recited the Elementary Learning and the Doctrine of the Mean, pondering deeply and practicing diligently. He would sleep only briefly after the night was far advanced. He named his study hall the Hall of Reverence, and he cultivated such discipline as to maintain ritual propriety at all times, never losing his composure even in sudden circumstances.

    In his filial piety to his parents he was exemplary, and in performing sacrifices he was wholly sincere. His mother had once woven cloth and sewn it into garments for him. Each time he sacrificed, he would wear these garments and, reciting the Tang poem lines "The tender care of mother's hands, the thread she wound," would weep. He charged his descendants that upon his death, these garments must be used in the burial.

    Toward his elder brother he showed filial respect, and to his kinsmen he was magnanimous. His wife's sister became a widow without children; when gravely ill, she begged to make the Minister's son her heir and sought to transfer all her property to him. The Minister demurred, saying, "Surely you should divide it among the brothers to preserve family bonds," and through many exchanges he refused, though she would not yield.

    In managing his household he maintained propriety, bringing harmony and dignity to both inner and outer quarters. He was particularly faithful in friendship—at weddings and funerals, condolences and gifts were carried out with meticulous care. His devotion to human relationships was exemplary. Throughout his life he did not pursue material gain, living simply in dress and food, eating only rice gruel when famine came. He delighted in encouraging scholar-officials, displaying their merits while concealing their faults, so that his gate never lacked guests, yet all were welcomed with sincerity, earning both love and respect.

    Serving four successive reigns, his concern for the nation's welfare matched his care for his own household. He labored from dawn to dusk, and in governing affairs proceeded with caution, never acting hastily but always with profound deliberation. In cases of great legal doubt, the King would always consult him for decision. In all matters concerning relations with neighbors and the state's secrets, there was no consultation he did not make, and the Minister never withheld his counsel. Whenever affairs of state could be questioned or approved, regardless of whether it concerned his position, he would lean against the wall all night, deliberating ceaselessly, then present his views with incisive directness. Sometimes the King heeded his counsel, sometimes not, yet later events often proved him right.

    He devoted special effort to agricultural promotion, the founding of schools, the cultivation of talent, and the improvement of customs. His other achievements in drawing upon both ancient and modern precedents to arbitrate disputes and establish the realm's direction cannot all be recorded. When he became Prime Minister, he increasingly took as his charge the assistance of the sovereign and the welfare of the people, his patriotic devotion never slackening until death. Such were his loyalty and diligence.

    Alas! The Minister possessed from the start the capacity for great statecraft, and was nurtured by the learning of the nature-principle school. Thus his counsels and policies embodied the great principles, great laws, great loyalty, and great rectitude, shining with brilliant splendor throughout the age. He was truly a great minister among ministers.

    His consort was the Virtuous Lady Park of Ningwol, from a great clan of that region. Her father was the Grand Censor of the Office of Remonstrance, posthumously titled Lianghe, named Kyŏng. Her maternal grandfather was the Chief Counselor to the State Council, named You-gyŏl. She was clear in mind and grave in manner, possessing all the virtues befitting a woman of quality. She bore two sons: The elder, Hu, distinguished himself in the examination of the year Byŏngo and later achieved the doctorate in the supplementary examination of Byŏngchin. He served as Counselor, Vice Chief of Staff, Councilor for the Heir Apparent's Court, Director of the Hall of Literary Treasures, Drafter of Edicts, Editor of the Hall of Historical Records, and concurrently Commander of the Military Equipment Bureau and Judge of Criminal Affairs. The younger, Nul, served as a minor official and Director of the Wine Bureau. She bore three daughters: The eldest married Choe Yu-jong, Left Advisor to the Heir Apparent; the second married Chŏng Cham, Governor of Pyŏngsan; the third married the examination graduate Yin Mi-kyŏm.

    Vice-Chief Hu married the daughter of Yi Hung-mun, Governor of Hŭnghae County, fathering three sons: the eldest named Sŏ, the second named Tam, the third named Tun; and four daughters, all young. Director Nul married the daughter of Min Po-mun, Assistant in the Ministry of Households, and fathered three sons named Sŏ, Tam, and Tun.

    Left Advisor Yu-jong fathered one son, Kyŏng-dong, and three daughters: the eldest married An Chŏl-son, Examiner of the Hall of Literary Treasures; the second married the scholar Yi Kŭk-bae; the third married the scholar Choe Yun-mun (not of the same clan). The Governor fathered one son, Suk-chŏng, a Recorder of the Western District, and three daughters, all young. The graduate fathered two sons, Ham and Chŏng, and two daughters, the elder married Hwang Sa-chin, a Recorder of the Bureau of Artisans, the younger still young. He left numerous descendants.

    The epitaph reads:

    Behold the vale of Hayang—
    the Heo clan renowned,
    where generation upon generation
    of illustrious souls have dwelt,
    who guard their virtue with reverence
    and perfect their conduct.
    They bestow their blessing on descendants,
    bringing forth Mungyeong,
    whose excellence unfolds
    the great fortune of his line.

    Icy as frozen dew his integrity,
    orderedly precise his bearing—
    he traverses the pathways
    of Zhu Xi and the Cheng brothers,
    wielding the wise counsel
    of Confucius and Mencius.

    Through four reigns he served,
    joying in the practice of learning—
    with embroidered statecraft
    and illuminated governance,
    without turtle's shell yet discerning,
    firm in judgment of uncertain matters;
    without mirror yet radiant,
    discerning the virtue and vice in men.

    Jade and cow-urine equally stored
    in the doctor's medicine chest,
    all materials selected for their use,
    all remedies proving efficacious
    in healing the realm.

    Where court policies were deficient
    or governance went awry,
    he exhausted his liver and gallbladder,
    his forthright words never ceasing.

    Taijong honored him, declaring:
    "This is my pillar and my support."
    The present King appointed him Prime Minister,
    raising him to bear the realm's burden.

    His plans for the kingdom run deep,
    his care for the people enduring—
    yet suddenly the grinding stone falls silent.
    What can be said to the azure heaven?

    His eldest son, of illustrious merit,
    preserves his filial devotion—
    let this epitaph be placed in the dark earth,
    shining through the endless ages.
